# Command bun

## What does this command do:

Bun is a fast, all-in-one JavaScript and TypeScript toolkit designed to serve as a high-performance alternative to Node.js. While Node.js uses Google's V8 engine, Bun is built on JavaScriptCore (the engine powering Safari), which is optimized for faster startup times and lower memory usage.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: curl -fsSL https://bun.com/install | bash
For Raspberry Pi install using: curl -fsSL https://bun.com/install | bash
For Mac install using: brew install oven-sh/bun/bun

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/.bun/bin/bun
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/.bun/bin/bun
For Mac run: /opt/homebrew/bin/bun

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://bun.com/docs

## Command options

# Run a TypeScript or JavaScript file
bun run ./my-script.ts

# Run a package.json script
bun run lint

# Run unit tests
bun test

# Execute a package binary, installing if needed (like npx)
bunx vite

# Start a REPL
bun repl

# Install dependencies from package.json
bun install
bun i

# Add a dependency
bun add hono
bun a hono

# Remove a dependency
bun remove left-pad
bun rm left-pad

# Update outdated dependencies
bun update react

# Bundle TypeScript/JavaScript into a single file
bun build ./a.ts ./b.jsx

# Initialize a new Bun project
bun init

# Create a new project from a template
bun create svelte
bun c svelte

# Upgrade Bun itself
bun upgrade

# Check installed packages for vulnerabilities
bun audit

# Show outdated dependencies
bun outdated

# Watch mode — restart on file change
bun run --watch ./server.ts

# Hot reload mode (no restart, live patch)
bun run --hot ./server.ts

# Check version
bun --version
bun --revision
